Avoid plugging emergency generators into electric outlets or hooking directly to home's electrical system putting you & lineworkers at risk
Keep generators outside and far from windows, doors & vents. Read BOTH the generator's label AND owner's manual & follow the instructions.
NEVER use a generator inside a home, basement, shed or garage even if doors and windows are open.
If your power is out, safely use a generator or battery-operated flashlights.
If you have a flooded basement in your home, never attempt to turn off power or operate circuit breakers while standing in water.
If your home has flood water inside or around it, don’t walk or wade in it. The water may be contaminated by oil, gasoline, or raw sewage.
Emergency workers may be assisting people in flooded areas or cleaning up debris. Help them by staying off the roads as much as possible.
Avoid downed power/utility lines as they may be live with deadly voltage. Stay away & report immediately to your power or utility company.
Avoid debris, downed power lines & flood water, which may be electrically charged, hiding dangerous debris or places washed away ground.
If you evacuated and are planning to return home, return to the area ONLY when local officials indicate it is safe to return.
Listen to local officials for updates and instructions. If told to evacuate, do so IMMEDIATELY. The window to get out is closing.
